There is no way that the US and the Republic of Vietnam (South Vietnam) could have won the war, because there was no particular goal it was fighting for. In 1954 at the conference in Geneva where Vietnamese independence from France was negotiated, the dual-government ("South" and "North" Vietnam) setup was instituted as a temporary measure. Reunification elections were supposed to be held in1956; they never were. The division was never meant to be permanent, so what could "victory" possibly have been? The ongoing existence of the Republic of Vietnam (South Vietnam), which was never a viable nation?
<p>
The only possible outcome which Americans might have thought of as closer to "winning" would have been a division of the country in perpetuity, with an armed truce and a militarized DMZ, exactly as in Korea. Would we really want to still  have troops patrolling an artifically created border to ensure the continued existence of a government so oppressive to its own citizens that Buddhist monks burned themselves to protest its repressions? Perhaps there are some Americans who would; I am not among them.
<p>
Whether one approves of the contemporary communist government of Vietnam or not, the nation of Vietnam is reunited, which fulfilled the goal of the1954 agreement; it is now an independent nation in charge of its own destiny, as much as any nation is in the modern world. At least it has no foreign military presence.
<p>
