In a sense, the war was lost before we sent in the first advisors.  You had a country that was an artificial creation. (Western powers have been playing at this since the carving up of Africa in the 1800s).  The head of government in the South was a transplanted northerner, as was much of his principle base of support, the Catholic minority.  The majority of the population was effectively disenfranchised.  The most popular leader was Ho Chi Minh, whom the US was afraid would win a general election.  The power vacuum created just became worse after Diem's assasination, and never really filled up.  
<p>
Most of the population just wanted to be left alone.  By day they paid for the graft of the National Police, and by night they paid the exactions of the local Viet Cong.  Businesses (both legal and illegal) and farms both contributed under duress to each side.
<p>
Here was a country that spent 800 years winning independence from China and had been involved in nearly continuous war since 1939, and we, the most impatient nation on the planet, were going to outlast and make the price too high for the North Vietnamese.  People like John Gavin tried to give the president, et al, a reality check, but were ignored.
<p>
The US never really faced the fact that the North would take 20 times our losses and still come back for more.  You cannot fight a limited war if your foe is fighting a total war.  Choosing to go forward without a declaration of war avoided facing some unpleasant truths which could have blocked entry into the war, but made it certain that the US would go in disunited and never fully committed.
<p>
The US policy makers never saw fit to learn in depth about Vietnam and Vietnamese until we were in over our heads.  Virtually every major principle of military strategy was violated, the assumption being that the American Way and modern technology would triumph.
<p>
The only possible way we could have won would have been to risk a general Asian war and try to conquer the North.  This would have taken more troops, cost more casualties on both sides, left us with communist guerillas in the jungles all over, a hostile Chinese border and a 20- to 40-year occupation.  All this coming out of an undeclared war would have put an unbearable strain on our own country.
<p>
Leaving aside the moral questions for just a moment, we got into a fight we could not and would not finish.

