I saw first-hand the glut of "contractors" at Long Binh. Fortunes were made. Black market runs across the Cambodian border to Diamond City were a regular affair;  we often tracked them on radar after midnight. For some reason we couldn't fire on those suckers. The government system of Vietnam really was high on the hog. Waste was everywhere. No one cared.  The soldier sat in the mud or the dust with the rats, bugs, corruption, and everything else, and got the bad food, the raw deal, nothing.
<p>
While I was there, I sensed that the war was placed on a slow boil on purpose. We had more than enough resources to end it quickly. The tip-off was the bald-faced lie about body count. When I left the 1st Division for the 25th, I was told that I had at least "200 gooks" under my belt. Bullshit. It was more important to me how many grunts I supported, protected and saved.
<p>
I feel the Vietnam War went slowly sour between 1966 and 1968/69. At that point, I believe the war was fueled and modulated more by greed than by political need. I feel the conflict started with "good" intentions but ended up a disaster and a billboard for the baser side of our national character.
