Subject: Two Minor Incidents Lead to Consequences
<p>
1. An Armored Personnel Carrier (APC) was tooling northbound on Hwy 1 south of Bong Son, Binh Dinh Province headed for LZ English [a landing zone toward the north].  The right lever broke, and the driver panicked, forgetting to hit the brakes and/or kill the motor.  With the left lever still engaged to the left track, the vehicle pivoted on the disconnected right track, plowed through a stucco covered brick wall, over three chickens and a fruit tree, and into the southwest corner of a rather substantial house.  No one was hurt, and within an hour, the APC was aboard a lowboy (a large trailer meant for hauling armored vehicles) moving again towards LZ English.
<p>
Somehow our brigade civil affairs officer never found the time to interview the lady who owned the property, much less assist her in filling out the damage claim forms, as was his job.  Not knowing where else to go, she went to the local district police chief in Bong Son for help.  This is like saying "Help!" to Louis the Loan Shark.  He agreed to help her prepare the paperwork, and see to it that all was forwarded to the Americans.  As we later learned, the assistance came at a price, namely 50 percent of the damage claim.
<p>
The damage claim was for $26,000.  I was assigned to be the damage claims officer.  First, I made an appointment with the village chief, who turned out to be a good, honest man.  The two of us had to find out the cost of building materials and labor for the house and wall (we even visited a brickmaker to get a cost on bricks), the age and size of the fruit tree - to calculate the value of normal fruit production over its expected lifespan, and the age of the chickens - to calculate the value of eggs which would be produced over their expected lifespans.  The final figure was approx. $8,500.
<p>
The lady never saw a cent because as far as the police chief was concerned, she owed him $13,000.  Ah, yes, winning the hearts and minds.  Good thing I never saw the civil affairs officer after that, or I might have gotten in trouble for speaking improperly to a superior officer.
<p>
2. Like a lot of American bases, we had Vietnamese or Korean barbers, local mama-sans cleaning our hooches, and preteen boys shining our boots.  Security clearances for these persons were under the District Police Chief of the Vietnamese National Police.  Yup, same guy.  As mentioned before, I was in a military intelligence (MI) company.       
     <p>                                                             
Therefore, it wasn't long before our new Commanding Officer (CO) found out that the police chief was selling security clearances. To a career MI officer used to working in the recesses of the Pentagon where you couldn't sneeze without a proper security clearance, this was intolerable.  Our commanding officer decided to make our shoeshine boy a test case.  He told the kid not to pay the bribe, and that he would back him up.  For three weeks there was a back-and-forth with the police chief.  A letter then came to our commanding officer from MACV in Saigon, saying "Cease and desist."  You're rocking the boat and upsetting our ally."  Some word must have reached the police chief at the same time, as the shoeshine boy's clearance was pulled the next morning.
<p>
Later we got word, that the police chief, in order to cover himself in any possible future investigation, had worked up a dossier on an imaginary Viet Cong uncle for the kid which was used to prevent his admission to high school.  
<p>
With friends like these........
<p>
I often wonder what happened to our shoeshine boy and the honest village chief I met.  As for the police chief, I'm tempted by some very unchristian thoughts.
<p>
