Tom,
<p>
The 1000 meter buffer around villes or hamlets was a political thing, a real joke, and close to criminal, as far as I am concerned.
<p>
We could register 105's to within 50 meters or so. 155's and 8"'s to 10 to 20 meters. Azimuth error with good meteroligical data +/- negligible. We even compensated for the rotation of the earth on long-range shots.  Range errors were a little more dicey, but good registration for each powder lot about eliminated that. If the (respectfully) gun bunnies made a mistake on the charge in the canister, and that did happen very rarely, you would have a long or short round. That was the only scary part in the heat of a fire mission. We could put beautiful time on targets with perfect height of burst routinely. Fire cracker coverage was always on the money. We had superb equipment and field hardened digital computers, FADACs (by Motorola, I think) that could do your gun data 15 percent better than any stick!
<p>
175 guns were used only well out of the range of any grunts or habitations. Guns are very sloppy (no rifling), especially at high angle.  We used to have to get B52 clearance out of Guam to do high angle over Nui Ba Den for intel targets on the other side.
<p>
In a pinch, and with a good FO*, we could work 105 rounds within 200 meters without a problem. Heavies worked out a little farther because of the effects of the detonation of the round.
<p>
The 1000 meter buffer (1500 in some places) was one of the rules of engagement that made me sick at heart.
<p>
