Arthur,
<p>
It's great to get some perspective from someone who knows about the guns.  
<p>
One night as we slept in Quang Ngai, suddenly there were a dozen huge explosions that shook us awake, much louder than the 82mm mortars of the Viet Cong into town.  Next day we learned that, luckily, the only casualty was a cow in a pasture outside of town.
<p>
Couple weeks later we visited "Artillery Hill" where Capt. Heard invited my wife and me into the bunker to show us his maps for the huge 175mm guns he ran there.  He showed us the four quadrants on the map  with their guns at the center.  Then he told us the firing order consisted of seven numbers, the first number being the quadrant, the next three being the latitude and the final three being the longitude.
<p>
I happened to mention to him the dozen huge explosions near our town.  With a sheepish grin, he confessed,  "That was us.  In the middle of the night, someone got the first number wrong.  We fired into quadrant two instead of three.  And Quang Ngai town was close by."
<p>
Does any of this make sense?
<p>
